[Leather panel] Gilt leather panel with a symmetrical pattern of curving floral strapwork, enclosing spaces fitted in with festoons, and in between them some flowers. The flowers have been painted in various colours, the strapwork is gilded, the ground red, Italy, ca. 1500-1700.

fields.physical_description:
[Leather panel] Gilt leather panel with a symmetrical pattern of curving floral strapwork, enclosing spaces fitted in with festoons, and in between them some flowers. The flowers have been painted in various colours, the strapwork is in gold, the ground red. The gilded and silvered parts have been punched with several different stamps. This panel was part of a large hanging, described originally as: Gilt leather hanging consisting of four panels, with six borders at the top and the bottom. The pattern consists of curving floral strapwork in gold and silver, enclosing spaces fitted in with festoons in gold, silver and colours, on a red ground. The border are ornamented with upright floral scrolls, tulips and other flowers in silver, gold, and colours, on a red ground. The panel is further decorated with small stamped diapers.

fields.history_note:
Formerly described as 'Florentine, 16th century'. There is, however, no exact information available (not in Italy or elsewhere) to keep this attribution any longer standing. The whole group of  panels and hangings that were acquired from Bardini were, without any exception, being described in this way, although for instance inventory number 732-1890 has proven to be of a Dutch origin. Information supplied by Eloy Koldeweij, October 1996.

Purchase price of £1000 for a group of leather objects (museum numbers: 682-1890 to 732-1890).
